'''Tochigi City Ōhira Museum of History and Folklore''' (栃木市おおひら歴史民俗資料館) is a museum located in {{ill|Ōhira Town Nishiyamada|ja|大平町西山田|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōhira Town Nishiyamada|qq=}}, Tochigi City, Tochigi Prefecture, Japan. It exhibits some of Japan’s largest boat-shaped wooden coffins and assembly wooden coffins, including items designated as [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]] from the {{ill|Shimotsuke Nanamawari Kagamitsuka Kofun|ja|下野七廻り鏡塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsuke Nanamawari Kagamitsuka Kofun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.<ref name="his"/>
Additionally, this article covers the adjacent '''Tochigi City Ōhira Local History Museum "Shiraishi Family Chief Official Residence"''' (栃木市おおひら郷土資料館「白石家戸長屋敷」), which is located east of the main museum. This facility uses the entire estate of the Shiraishi family, who served as local leaders (戸長) during the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji period]].<ref name="his"/> ...
